rossi-c fit overview

Pawel Sadlowski

rossi-c was fit to data preprocessed with RP method B and limited to 10 most popular items. Price shock was left unscaled.

v3b1_rossi model was used with k=30

Runtime ranged 0.5h and max memory use was not measured. RDS fit file measures approx. 900MB.

No sampling issues

\(\hat{R}\)

## [1] 6.412162

On average, there are 6-7 observations per customer, which is definitely a low figure considering that there are 12 individual-specific parameters to be estimated. On the other hand, this probably shouldn’t contribute to bad mixing. It could also be caused by low variability in prices, I guess.

Cross-comparison

data.frame( pars = names( rhat),
            rhat = rhat,
            ess_bulk = apply( posterior[,,names( rhat)], 3, ess_bulk),
            ess_tail = apply( posterior[,,names( rhat)], 3, ess_tail)) -> plotdata
rm( ess, rhat)
ggplot( plotdata) +
  geom_point( aes( x = ess_bulk, y = rhat, color = rhat > 1.03)) +
  ggtitle( 'Reltionship between Rhat and Bulk ESS values') +
  xlab( 'Bulk ESS') + ylab( 'Rhat')

ggplot( plotdata) +
  geom_point( aes( x = ess_tail, y = rhat, color = rhat > 1.03)) +
  ggtitle( 'Reltionship between Rhat and Tail ESS values') +
  xlab( 'Tail ESS') + ylab( 'Rhat')

lapply( 1:data$M, function( ii) {
  ggplot(
  data.frame( 
    x = apply( posterior[,,grep( paste0( 'beta\\[\\d+,', ii, '\\]'),

    ggtitle( 'KDE of mean product-specific intercept by domain',
             sub = sprintf( 'Product %i', ii)) +
    xlab( 'Parameter value') + ylab( '')
})

  data.frame( 
    id = as.factor( rep( 1:data$M, length( data$x))),
    price = do.call( c, lapply( data$x, function( y) y[,data$K]))

  ggtitle( 'Histogram of (transformed) prices by product') +
  xlab( 'Price (transformed)') + ylab( '') +
  theme( legend.position = 'none')
